{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653258"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:44:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18566"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18566"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.87,0,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114177"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11298"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96177"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10520"},{"type":"tags","id":"10539"},{"type":"tags","id":"10545"},{"type":"tags","id":"10547"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26202"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114177"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman with severe chronic obstructive pulmonary disease develops worsening hypercapnia. After five days, her arterial blood gas shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.32 (7.35-7.45)\u003Cbr /\u003EPCO2 65 mmHg (35-45)\u003Cbr /\u003EBicarbonate 32 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the renal response to chronic respiratory acidosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased hydrogen ion excretion","Increased bicarbonate reabsorption and hydrogen ion excretion","Decreased ammonium ion production","Increased bicarbonate excretion","Decreased bicarbonate reabsorption"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen blood CO2 levels rise, it combines with water to form carbonic acid, leading to acidosis. The kidneys compensate by increasing proximal tubular bicarbonate reabsorption, enhancing distal tubular hydrogen ion secretion, and increasing ammonium ion production. \u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased bicarbonate reabsorption and hydrogen ion excretion\u003C/strong\u003E represents the correct compensatory response that develops over 3-5 days, resulting in increased plasma bicarbonate concentration which helps buffer the acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased bicarbonate reabsorption\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased bicarbonate excretion\u003C/strong\u003E would both worsen acidosis by reducing blood bicarbonate levels. \u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased hydrogen ion excretion\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased ammonium ion production\u003C/strong\u003E would reduce the kidney\u0027s ability to eliminate acid and impair the compensatory response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Respiratory acidosis causes increased renal bicarbonate reabsorption and hydrogen ion excretion to compensate for elevated blood CO2.","The kidney\u0027s response to respiratory acidosis takes 3-5 days to fully develop.","Renal compensation involves both increased proximal tubule bicarbonate reabsorption and increased distal tubule hydrogen ion secretion."],"references":["Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 31; pg. 414","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96177"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18566"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96177"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T11:36:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T11:36:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11298"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114177"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"}